Tasmania floods briefing

JUST TO UPDATE EVERYONE ... THE LATEST POLICE ALERT

Due to flooding, police and emergency services are currently evacuating Newstead, between Birch Avenue and Hoblers Bridge Road.

Residents are asked to please make their way safely to a nearby place of safety. There is an evacuation centre open at the Albert Hall, Launceston (corner of Cimitiere and Tamar Streets).

Please remember, if you are relocating, don't forget to take your medicines, valuables, documents, change of clothes, mobile phone & charger, toiletries and pets (preferably in cage), and register with the Council.

To all our wonderful Facebook friends in George Town!!!

You are all cordially invited to participate in a local positive story about your town!

The Examiner wants to celebrate the amazing amount of local sporting talent that has come out of George Town. From Brendon Bolton to Brad Green, Xavier Doherty, Danny Clark and so many more, the sporting stars that George Town has produced is really incredible. Here at The Examiner we want to really celebrate that, to celebrate the community and to show what really is so great about George Town.

To do this, we need the whole community to come together. We have already recruited the families of some of George Town's biggest local sporting stars but we need your help. We need as many people as possible (we're really hoping for at least 500) to come out and celebrate the town so we can take a giant photo for our front page. Come out in your George Town colours and join in our photo.

We would also love it if everyone can share this post so as many people as possible can read it.

Meet us at the George Town Football Oval at 11am this Saturday (tomorrow) and join in the celebration.

Hope you can all make it!

Okay everyone ... it's competition time. And this is a ripper

Mention the name Michael Flatley, and most people think Riverdance - or more recently Lord of the Dance.

The world's most successful dance show is about to explode onto the Australian stage from September 10 opening in Hobart with a spectacular new staging of Flatley's masterpiece - Lord of the Dance: Dangerous Games.

The theatrical extravaganza will then tour to Perth, Adelaide, Melbourne, Canberra, Brisbane, Gold Coast and Sydney.

Flatley's new show Dangerous Games has exciting and ground-breaking new technology, including holographs, dancing robots, world champion acrobats, and 34 of the greatest Irish Dancers in the world. A new score composed by Gerard Fahy, new choreography, stunning new costumes and special effect lighting add a breath-taking new dimension to
the original masterpiece.

Thanks to the promoters, The Examiner has FIVE DOUBLE PASSES for the Hobart performance to give away to our Facebook friends. The tickets are for the Thursday, September 10 performance at 8pm. Each double pass is valued at $199.80 for the double.

To go in the running to win, all you have to do is tell us in what country was Michael Flatley born by posting the answer below? (Hint: don't assume, okay?) Five people will be selected at random as winners. They will be notified through Facebook. We will stop registering entries at midnight tonight, so get tapping ... I mean, cracking!!!

status_message: Good day, all! Here's what's happening around the country today.

Congratulations to all our award winners, runners-up, nominees, coaches, parents and friends involved in junior sport across Tasmania. Without your participation and support there would be no awards to hand out at our Examiner IGA Junior Sports awards

Bailey Groves is the well-deserved winner of the Male Individual Award. His amazing talents in ISSF air pistol target shooting have seen him represent Australia in his sport and we are excited to see what the future brings for Bailey.
What a champion! Ariarne Titmus has broken records, won gold and selectors are already keeping an eye on her for the 2020 Olympic swimming team. Ariarne just received the Female Individual Award.
Amy Halaby is certainly a talent to be jealous of! She just won the All Round Athlete Award for her involvement in touch football, soccer and little athletics.
Courtney Webb plays cricket, AFL, tennis, basketball, athletics and she is the winner of this year's Encouragement Award. Definitely an athlete to watch.
Examiner Sports editor Rob Shaw interviewing Jake Birthwhistle at the junior sports awards right now

A big thank you goes to the winners of the Service to Sport Award who have worked tirelessly with young people to make Tasmanian sport what it is today. The winners are Rodney Lockett, Zac Partridge, Emma Whyte, Tenielle McDermott, Jock Glass, Nathan Warren and Shannon Williams.
link_name: Photos from The Examiner Newspaper, Launceston's post

The Liberal Party has promised to loosen the speed limits imposed on P1 drivers in Tasmania.
Currently, P1 drivers have a max speed of 80 km/h. The Liberals say they will increase that max speed limit to 100km/h on roads with a 110km/h speed limit and 90km/h on roads with a 100km/ h speed limit.

status_message:
Launceston teacher Robert Lewandowski has completed his 3000km bike ride to raise $$ for cystic fibrosis ... congratulations Robbie ... this is his final diary entry he posted to us:


The final day. 150 km. Left Snow Town at 6.15 am. Along the way to Adelaide I saw hot houses, that were growing tomatoes, olive groves and fields of wheat and barley. It was odd to think that I had 150 km to ride but I was taking it like a Sunday stroll. Today I chose not to listen to my music but enjoy the last day of riding. I rode past Churches and the iconic Adelaide Oval towards the Westpac branch on King William Street. On arrival I was greeted by several Westpac employees, a CF mum and my gorgeous and patient wife Rachael. I was relived to have finally have finished this epic ride. 3061 km in 20 days of riding. Wow wee, thank heaps everyone for your support.

http://www.examiner.com.au/story/1855847/tradies-leaving-in-droves/?cs=94
Great work Rob ... congratulations on your amazing effort!

The latest from Riverside High School teacher Rob Lewandowski, who is cycling to from Darwin to Adelaide to raise funds for Cystic Fibrosis:
''Last night's meal at the Eldo Hotel in Woomera was the best meal I have eaten on my journey from Darwin to Adelaide. 
It fuelled me for today's ride to Port Augusta, 181km. Along the ride today I came across a car towing a trailer with it's wheel blown out. I offered them my spare inner tube but this offer was kindly declined. 
The family gave a donation which was very pleasing considering the situation they were faced with. 
Due to favourable conditions I managed to arrive in Port Augusta by lunchtime. With only two days of riding readers are reminded that donations may be made by either:
Westpac account: Cystic Fibrosis Tasmania - Rob's Ride 
BSB 037001 ACC No 641343;

or the Every Day Hero Page www.give.everydayhero.com/au/rob-lewandowski 
If you want to leave a message of support or like my Facebook page it is:
www.facebook.com/RobsRideForCysticFibrosis''
Good morning everyone! How are you spending your Sunday?

Here's the latest update from Riverside High School teacher Rob Lewandowski, who is cycling to from Darwin to Adelaide to raise funds for Cystic Fibrosis:
''The day was one of the hardest days riding I have ever done. The wind was relentless. 
The feeling of satisfaction when I had completed the day was awesome. 
The recovery pool was very cold but just what was needed at the end of such a big day. I woke this morning after a sleep in to find that Luke Hodge, Hawthorn Captain, had left a message on my Facebook page. That was really inspiring. 
''Today's ride was only 121 km to Woomera, which is a very interesting town, like a ghost town. ''

''Today started with a mad dash to find arm warmers, leg warmers and gloves, a chilli 8 degrees greeted me at 5am. 
After 20 km in I crossed the border into South Australia. I travelled the 192 km in about 7 hours making great time with a slight tail wind. 
Once in Marla I jumped into the pool for some recovery, then it was off to lunch. 
An Army artillery unit from Darwin also had the same idea and were very generous with their donation towards the cause. ''

if you love cats, they you'll love our readers' gallery of 'Fantastic Felines' ... you can check it out here ..

http://www.examiner.com.au/story/1842218/readers-gallery-fantastic-felines/?cs=94

Here's another update from Rob Lewandowski, who sent us this late last night. 
"Yesterday was a much welcomed rest day. Took the bike in for a service, nothing was wrong with it just wanted to make sure. Had a massage for one and a half hours, which was needed. Felt very rested at the end of the day. Today started well heading out of Alice Springs at a good pace. Once I turned onto the Stuart highway things changed. The wind picked up and was heading straight towards me. Not a bad thing if you were just going for a Sunday ride to the fish shop ( Rosvears ) but a real problem when you have to ride 200 km with no chance of turning around. 11 hours later arrival at Erldunda was a great feeling."

''After two gruelling 40+ degree days and covering 310 km I have reached Ti Tree. During yesterday's ride i passed the Devil Marbles which were very impressive. 
Last night stop over was at Wycliffe Well, Australia's UFO capital and today journey saw a drop in to the Barrow Creek Historic Pub for breakfast after a 4.30 am depart. 
Forecast for tomorrow has Alice Springs at 33 degrees a drop of 10 which should make for a much more pleasant ride. A rest day to follow on Saturday.''

status_message: Hello parents...following on from the message yesterday about the Schoolkids Bonus, the federal government is hoping to axe the bonus by the end of the year so there will be no payment for children heading to school in January. Considering so many people said it was a great help this year - how do you feel now knowing it may be axed? And would any family be keen to be in story? If so, give me a call on 6336 7362. Cheers

Here's a submission to our Launceston Show smartphone assignment, sent in by Mark Shadbolt.
"Jenna Shadbolt ready to go on the bungee trampoline!"

Here's the latest update from Riverside High School teacher Rob Lewandowski, who is cycling to from Darwin to Adelaide to raise funds for Cystic Fibrosis, about his day yesterday:
''Well, what a day! Started out as normal, up at 4.45 and on the road by 5 am. The road had some long gradual climbs, one was over 10 km long. To make this even more enjoyable the thermometer hit 43. With the sun reflecting back off the Tarmac I think it might have even been higher than that. The pool at the caravan park was much needed and very refreshing. ''

Families were able to access the federal government's School Kids Bonus this year to help parents buy shoes, books etc before students started school - do you think the bonus was a good thing to help families get ready for school? And what did you spend it on?
Hey everyone! Is there any motor racing fans out there that are heading to Bathurst this weekend for the great race? If so, we'd love to catch up for a story.

Here's the latest from Rob Lewandowski 
"Day six started out at 5am to find the back tyre flat, replaced the tube in the dark and started towards Elliott. About 4 km down the road the tube burst with a bang. I must of pinched the tube under the tyre, a rookie error. This time I had to call my support crew to bring backup. The rest of the ride went well even though I was in a crabby mood. Today I completed the journey from Elliott to Renner Springs, 92 km easily but did have one flat tyre. Was passed by several solar world challenge cars which are very slick and high tech. Cars travel at speeds close to 100km per hour. Off to Tennant Creek tomorrow. I have said farewell to support crew 1, Brady and Stuart and hello to Jonno, support crew 2."

Labor is set to lose three of its four seats in Tasmania with Franklin's Julie Collins the only Labor MHR to survive the massive swing against the government.

On Wednesday morning Tasmania lost a remarkable musician with the death of Philip ``Picasso'' Crothers. Crothers was well known across Australia as frontman of The Fabulous Picasso Brothers and drummer in 1980s rock band Devils in Heaven. He passed away in a single vehicle crash at Deviot. The Examiner would like to pass on its condolences to Crothers' wife Kathy, his family and friends. Tasmania has lost something very special. A talented man taken far too early ...

http://www.examiner.com.au/story/1678489/crash-victim-a-local-legend-shining-star/?cs=94

Tasmania Police have just provided an update on missing German backpacker Margarida Farinha.

Cricket update:

TASMANIA'S bowlers are backing up their batsmen to keep the hosts in control in the Sheffield Shield final against Queensland.
All of the Tigers' strike bowlers have claimed a wicket to have the Bulls 4-104 at tea on day three.
A rain-delayed afternoon session saw first-change bowlers Evan Gulbis and James Faulkner both have batsmen caught behind by Tim Paine.
The dangerous pair of Nathan Reardon and Joe Burns went for 13 and 6 respectively, the latter a superb if debatable one-hander by the keeper.
Peter Forrest remains the front line of resistance on 42, supported by last year's player of the final Chris Hartley (10).
Do you like rain?

RAIN has forced an early lunch on day three of the Sheffield Shield final but not before Tasmania had claimed another wicket to keep its nose in front in the contest.
Queensland was 1-12 overnight in reply to the Tigers' 419 and yesterday's batting hero Luke Butterworth justified his all-rounder status by claiming the only wicket of the shortened morning session.
Luke Pomersbach was dismissed in similar style to fellow opener Greg Moller when Butterworth had him clean bowled for 17.
Peter Forrest (28) and Nathan Reardon (6) saw the Bulls to 2-60, still 359 behind when a downpour swept in from the western shore to bring a premature end to the session.

Ben Hilfenhaus took a wicket off the first ball of Queensland's innings as the Bulls stumbled to 1-12 at stumps of the second day of the Sheffield Shield final in Hobart. Earlier Tasmania was dismissed for 419. Read Rob Shaw's stumps report below, with his full wrap-up of the days play in tomorrow's Sunday Examiner.

status_message: Great little afternoon poll from our friends at X-Static ...

We've received our first childhood memory from Kirsty Henderson! 

''This is Pink Teddy. I loved Pink Teddy for the first 2 1/2 years of my life, one fateful day I lost Pink Teddy and I thought he was gone for good (very tragic for a 2 1/2 year old). But then nearly 10 years after Pink Teddy was lost I was with my mother while she was taking my newborn baby brother to the child health clinic and what do you know Pink Teddy was in the nurse's office hanging off the scales, the nurse had been there all of those years and never lost hope that the owner would be found. It took 10 years but we were reunited that day. That was nearly 30 years ago now and Pink Teddy has been kept safe and sound ever since.''

Thanks Kirsty!

With our website down, Facebook provides the perfect platform for us to post our stories here ... like this one from our local government reporter, Patrick Billings ...

New tip levy ... 

The Launceston City Council has backed a statewide waste levy of $10 a tonne that would raise about $1 million a year from its Remount Road tip. 

The levy would be passed on through higher tip charges in the hope it would reduce the 100,000 tonnes of landfill buried at the tip each year. 

Under the levy, fees for cars and single-axle trailers using the Launceston tip would rise by about $1.30 and $2.50 respectively. 

The council has already proposed a 4 per cent increase in its annual waste management charge for all ratepayers and increases in tip fees of between 8 and 12 per cent. 

And it comes as households face significant increases in power and water and sewerage charges.

DO YOU THINK AN INCREASE IN TIP FEES WILL REDUCE THE AMOUNT OF RUBBISH?

Science-fiction classic flick Blade Runner has been voted the greatest sci-fi film of all time.
A readers' poll by SFX magazine voted the Ridley Scott directed cult movie, starring Harrison Ford, the greatest ahead of The Empire Strikes Back and Aliens.
More than 10,000 votes were cast in the poll, which will be published in a special edition magazine - SFX Presents: The Top 100 Science Fiction, Fantasy And Horror Movies Of All Time. 
THE TOP 10
1. Blade Runner 
2. The Empire Strikes Back 
3. Aliens 
4. Star Wars 
5. The Lord Of The Rings: The Fellowship Of The Ring 
6. The Matrix 
7. Serenity 
8. Alien 
9. Back To The Future 
10. The Dark Knight 

Do you agree with the list?
What movie has missed out?
What is your favourite sci-fi movie of all time?

status_message:
TASMANIA Police have confirmed that three men have died overnight while camping at Miena near the Great Lakes.
Duty sergeant John Ford said the men were found this morning and the deaths were not suspicious.
He said police would not comment further until all next of kin had been notified.
It is unknown how the men died but there are reports that a gas bottle had leaked into their caravan killing them.
Do you know more?

Blokey mag FMH (For Him Magazine) has gone under. The once man-mag powerhouse, which featured articles on buxom babes, sex, sport, grog and gadgets will be axed after its May edition. But do people even read ANY 'girly mags' any more?

Good morning Facebookers, how did you sleep? Did the overnight rain help you get some extra zzzzs?? Well, today is World Sleep Day - a celebration of sleep and a day of awareness of sleep issues ... but who really gets enough sleep?

Uggh, daylight savings ends in a few weeks (April 1 to be precise) ... has anyone noticed how dark it is of a morning?? Do you think it's time for Tasmania to adopt daylight savings all-year-round? Or do you think it should stay the way it is?

And the good news is ... the graffiti on the wall in Brisbane Street - which featured some rather unsavoury language - has finally been removed. Dare I suggest because of the public uproar and the story in the paper??
